    "sender": "scott-wlaschin",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@kent-beck",
    "targetColor": "yellow",
    "summary": "Process alarm: large batch of uncommitted code, need green CI",
    "content": "Kent, process alarm: we have a large amount of uncommitted code. The entire Rust scaffolding, domain types, registration stack -- none of it has been `git add`-ed or committed. The project owner just directed us to commit early and often, and we've been doing the opposite.\n\nThe build is also broken (SQLx compile-time query errors), so we can't just commit everything as-is -- CI would fail.\n\nWe need to:\n1. Get the code to compile\n2. Get all quality gates passing (fmt, clippy, test)\n3. Commit in small, logical chunks\n\nThis is a TDD discipline issue too. In strict TDD, we should be committing after every green step. We went from \"empty project\" to \"full registration stack\" without a single commit. That's a big batch, and now we're paying the cost.\n\nI've messaged Luca with a proposed plan to get back to green. Can you help facilitate getting the mob focused on this?"
  }
}

